    epigraph: '“What we call talent is usually just the practice we never saw.”',
    body: `<p><strong>Core claim:</strong> We instinctively attribute extraordinary ability to an inborn gift, but the authors argue this is a misleading myth. The overwhelming majority of performances we label as talent are in fact grown through years of correct practice, not handed down by some innate endowment.</p><p><strong>The argument:</strong> Crediting achievement to talent sounds like praise, but it is really a form of surrender. It implies that effort is pointless and that the rankings were fixed by genes long ago. That ceiling is exactly what the authors want to tear down: once you see that ability can be shaped, the method of practice becomes the question that truly matters. They repeatedly stress that behind almost every seemingly impossible performance lies an overlooked and remarkably intense history of training.</p><div class="section-break">◆ ◆ ◆</div><p><strong>Key study / example:</strong> Absolute (perfect) pitch has long been treated as a rare gift only a lucky few are born with. Yet when the Japanese researcher Ayako Sakakibara put a group of young children through systematic training, nearly all of them acquired perfect pitch, an ability everyone had assumed could only be innate. Mozart is another familiar counterexample: he showed musical ability so early not because of some divine spark, but because his father, a music teacher, subjected him to intense, systematic early training from a very young age.</p><p><strong>Takeaway:</strong> Instead of asking, 'Do I have the talent for this?' ask, 'Have I practiced enough, in the right way?' Shift your focus from a fixed endowment to a shapeable process, and the boundary of what is possible for you moves dramatically outward.</p><p class="thought-question">🤔 Reflect: Have you ever given something up because you told yourself, 'I was just not born for this'? If that sentence turned out to be false, would you begin again?</p>`
