    epigraph: '“Repetition is not progress. Stepping out of the comfort zone is.”',
    body: `<p><strong>Core claim:</strong> Not all practice works. Most people engage in naive practice, mindlessly repeating something until it is merely good enough, then stalling and circling in place. Real progress comes from purposeful practice: it has clear, specific goals, demands full focus, provides immediate feedback, and continually pushes you out of your comfort zone.</p><p><strong>The argument:</strong> Naive practice fails because once an action becomes automatic and reaches a 'good enough' level, the brain stops improving. Years of further accumulation then amount to repeating the same thing thousands of times without gaining any ability. Purposeful practice breaks the vague wish to 'get better' into a series of measurable small goals, corrects course through constant feedback, and deliberately targets a difficulty just beyond your current reach, so that every session pushes the boundary outward.</p><div class="section-break">◆ ◆ ◆</div><p><strong>Key study / example:</strong> In a classic experiment the authors were involved with, the subject Steve Faloon began like anyone else, able to hold about 7 random digits in memory. But through purposeful practice, setting explicit goals, pushing to recall one more digit each time, immediately reviewing where he went wrong, and repeatedly breaking his own ceiling, he eventually recalled 82 digits in a single string. His raw short-term memory 'talent' never changed. What changed was the way he practiced and the strategies he built.</p><p><strong>Takeaway:</strong> Audit the practice you are doing right now. Does it have a specific goal? Full focus? Feedback? Does it make you strain? If all four are missing, you are probably just spending time inside your comfort zone rather than getting stronger.</p><p class="thought-question">🤔 Reflect: The thing you are most skilled at, is it still improving, or has it been parked at 'good enough' for years?</p>`
