    body: `<p><strong>Core claim:</strong> Practice works because the brain and body possess a remarkable capacity for adaptation. When you are pushed to the edge of your ability and your existing equilibrium (homeostasis) is disrupted, the body reshapes itself to meet the new demand. Practice genuinely changes the hardware, not merely polishes a routine.</p><p><strong>The argument:</strong> The body prefers stability. As long as you operate within a comfortable range, it has no reason to change. Only when you keep applying a challenge beyond your current load, approaching the limit and breaking that equilibrium, does the body launch a remodel: growing new connections, strengthening the relevant regions. This is why 'stepping out of the comfort zone' is not a motivational slogan but a physiological and neurological necessity for triggering change.</p><div class="section-break">◆ ◆ ◆</div><p><strong>Key study / example:</strong> London taxi drivers must memorize the city's tangled street network for the famous test known as The Knowledge. Researchers found that the hippocampus, the region handling spatial memory, grew visibly larger as they trained, the brain's physical structure altered by intense use. Musicians show the same pattern: years of training reshape the neural regions tied to their instrument. Both are direct evidence that practice rewrites the brain's hardware, the foundation of brain plasticity.</p><p><strong>Takeaway:</strong> Your brain is not a fixed container but a construction site that expands on demand. Whatever ability you want, you have to keep sending it the 'overload' signal, and only then will it build the matching structure for you.</p><p class="thought-question">🤔 Reflect: If the brain reshapes itself in whatever direction you push it, what have you mainly been sculpting it into over the past year?</p>`
