    epigraph: '“Experience piles up seniority, but not necessarily skill, unless you are truly practicing while you work.”',
    body: `<p><strong>Core claim:</strong> Here the author carries the principles of deliberate practice into the workplace and dismantles a widespread myth: the belief that ability rises automatically as long as you stay in a role long enough and gather enough experience. In reality, many professionals get up to speed quickly in their first few years and then plateau, or even slowly decline, because routine daily work does not by itself trigger the challenge and feedback that deliberate practice requires. The people and organizations that keep getting stronger are those that deliberately weave "learning on the job by doing with feedback" into the work itself.</p><p><strong>The argument:</strong> The author argues that the key to workplace mastery is replacing "mere accumulation of experience" with "deliberate practice that comes with feedback." That means designing training close to real conditions, yet repeatable and immediately reviewable, so workers can face hard challenges in a controlled setting, make mistakes, get feedback, and correct. Going further, he stresses that this should not be a one-off training course but a part of both organizational culture and personal routine, turning "continually practicing to raise performance" into an ongoing habit rather than an occasional event. A leader's job is to build an environment that keeps supplying challenge and feedback, so that everyone's mental representations keep upgrading.</p><div class="section-break">◆ ◆ ◆</div><p><strong>Key study / example:</strong> The author points to the U.S. Navy's Top Gun fighter school as a classic case. During the Vietnam War, the Navy found its air-combat exchange ratio was poor, so it set up rigorous training: pilots flew against a squadron of "aggressors" who simulated enemy tactics, and every dogfight was followed by an exhaustive debrief that dissected each decision as right or wrong. This is deliberate practice that approaches real conditions and comes with intense feedback. Pilots who went through it performed dramatically better in actual combat, and win rates improved markedly. The Top Gun example vividly shows that institutionalizing the principles of deliberate practice can produce measurable leaps even in a high-stakes, life-or-death domain.</p><p><strong>Takeaway:</strong> Do not mistake seniority for skill. If you want to keep breaking through in your career, actively design challenges for yourself, seek out honest feedback, and make that kind of practice the norm. If you are a manager, bring your whole team into an environment of continual practice and review, rather than relying on people simply "doing more until it feels familiar."</p><p class="thought-question">🤔 Reflect: In your current job, how much of your time goes to "repeating what you already know how to do," and how much to "deliberately challenging what you cannot yet do and getting feedback"? If the balance is off, what kind of "aggressor drill" could you design for yourself?</p>`
