  11: { num: 'Appendix · Reader’s Review', title: 'Learning on the Shoulders of Giants', epigraph: '“The moment you get distracted, or start finding your practice easy and fun, you have probably stopped improving.”　— Kun Han Le', body: `
<p><em>This is the site owner Kun Han Le’s own review of the book (first published on his personal blog in 2018, in a question-and-answer format). What follows is a faithful condensation, keeping his points and warnings.</em></p>
<p>The book is about the "deliberate practice" that Ericsson researched all his life, and it clears up many popular misconceptions along the way. Kun Han Le uses a series of questions and answers to lay it all out.</p>
<div class="section-break">◆ ◆ ◆</div>
<p><strong>Three kinds of practice, each a step higher.</strong> He first separates "naive practice" from "goal-directed practice": naive practice means drilling the basics until you are merely competent, then letting your skill plateau; goal-directed practice demands specific goals aimed at your weaknesses, intense focus, a simple feedback mechanism, and constantly stepping outside your comfort zone. "Deliberate practice" then goes further by adding "mental representations" — the cognitive structures that let experts process information efficiently; chess masters and top performers in every field rely on better mental models than the rest of us. He sums up deliberate practice as: <strong>"monitoring and evaluating your own performance, and adjusting your mental representations when needed to improve."</strong></p>
<div class="section-break">◆ ◆ ◆</div>
<p><strong>Its limits.</strong> He is honest about the preconditions: deliberate practice works best in fields that are already mature, with clear distinctions between expert and novice (music, dance, chess); and it needs a qualified teacher who can prescribe the right targeted activities. It cannot simply be bolted onto everything.</p>
<p><strong>The most common misunderstanding.</strong> He stresses that <strong>mere discomfort is not deliberate practice</strong>. Many people mistake being busy for making progress — genuine effort must connect to an ultimate goal and target specific weaknesses. This leads to the review’s most useful yardstick: <strong>the moment you get distracted in practice, or start finding it easy and fun, you have probably stopped improving.</strong></p>
<div class="section-break">◆ ◆ ◆</div>
<p><strong>Talent vs practice, and advice for the rest of us.</strong> He agrees with the book’s evidence: extensive, efficient practice determines achievement far more than innate talent; the brain’s plasticity lets us build abilities once thought inborn (even absolute pitch). As for putting it to use, his advice: break long-term goals into concrete short-term ones, keep full focus, get expert feedback wherever possible, and design a structured practice plan aimed at your identified weaknesses. That, in the end, is what it means to learn "on the shoulders of giants."</p>
<p class="thought-question">🤔 Reflect: Use Kun Han Le’s yardstick — "easy and fun probably means no progress" — on the activity you have poured the most hours into lately. Is it deliberate sharpening, or just comfortable repetition?</p>
`
  }
